<p>Zone 2 cardio has gone from elite endurance training concept to mainstream biohacking recommendation — largely thanks to Andrew Huberman and Peter Attia bringing the work of researcher Iñigo San Millán to a wider audience. The problem: most of the resulting content is frustratingly vague. "Low-intensity cardio" and "can hold a conversation" are not precise enough to train productively. Here's the actual protocol with numbers.</p>

<h2>What Zone 2 Actually Is</h2>

<p>Zone 2 refers to a specific metabolic state, not just a heart rate band. Understanding the metabolic definition makes the heart rate targets make sense.</p>

<p>In Zone 2, your body is running primarily on fat oxidation — using fat as the dominant fuel source — while maintaining a steady state of aerobic energy production. The key physiological marker: lactate levels remain low and stable, typically below 2 mmol/L. You're working hard enough to generate mitochondrial adaptations but not so hard that you're accumulating lactate and shifting into glycolytic (carbohydrate-burning) metabolism.</p>

<p>San Millán's research, conducted largely on professional cyclists, established that this specific metabolic zone produces profound mitochondrial adaptations over time — increasing mitochondrial density, improving fat oxidation capacity, and enhancing mitochondrial efficiency in a way that higher intensities don't replicate. The mitochondria are essentially being trained to do more work with less fuel.</p>

<h2>Zone 2 Heart Rate: How to Find Your Number</h2>

<p>The most commonly cited Zone 2 heart rate range is <strong>60–75% of your maximum heart rate</strong>. This is a reasonable starting point but it's an approximation — individual variation is significant enough that the conversation test and perceived exertion are important calibration tools alongside heart rate.</p>

<h3>Calculating Your Zone 2 Range</h3>
<p>Step 1: Estimate your max heart rate. The 220 - age formula is widely used but has well-documented limitations. A more accurate estimate: 208 - (0.7 × age), which is the Tanaka formula and performs better across age groups.</p>

<p>Example for a 35-year-old:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Tanaka max HR: 208 - (0.7 × 35) = 208 - 24.5 = <strong>~183 bpm</strong></li>
  <li>Zone 2 range: 60–75% = <strong>110–137 bpm</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>Example for a 45-year-old:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Tanaka max HR: 208 - (0.7 × 45) = 208 - 31.5 = <strong>~177 bpm</strong></li>
  <li>Zone 2 range: 60–75% = <strong>106–133 bpm</strong></li>
</ul>

<h3>The Conversation Test (Critical Calibration Tool)</h3>
<p>At the upper edge of true Zone 2, you should be able to speak in full sentences but find it noticeably effortful. You can have a conversation — you're not breathless — but you wouldn't want to give a presentation. If speaking is completely effortless, you're likely below Zone 2. If you can only get out a few words between breaths, you've drifted into Zone 3.</p>

<p>San Millán specifically uses the ability to sustain a normal conversation as a key real-world calibration. Elite athletes have lower heart rates at the top of Zone 2 than recreational athletes because their aerobic base is far more developed — which is why blanket heart rate rules fail to account for fitness level.</p>

<h3>The Lactate Test (Gold Standard, Rarely Practical)</h3>
<p>If you want to be precise, lactate testing during exercise is the actual gold standard — a blood lactate level of 1.7–2.0 mmol/L corresponds to the top of Zone 2. Some performance labs offer this. For most people, the conversation test + heart rate range is sufficient.</p>

<h2>Zone 2 vs HIIT: Why You Need Both</h2>

<p>A common question after hearing about Zone 2: does this mean I should stop doing high-intensity training? No — and San Millán's own research on elite athletes makes this clear. The optimal training model is <em>polarised</em>: roughly 80% of training volume in Zone 2, 20% at high intensity (Zone 4–5). What gets almost no training time is the middle — Zone 3, "moderate" cardio — which neither develops the aerobic base nor provides the high-intensity stimulus.</p>

<h3>What Zone 2 Develops:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Mitochondrial density and efficiency (the primary Zone 2 adaptation)</li>
  <li>Fat oxidation capacity — your ability to use fat as fuel at higher work rates</li>
  <li>Lactate threshold — by improving mitochondrial capacity to clear lactate</li>
  <li>Cardiovascular efficiency and stroke volume (heart pumping more blood per beat)</li>
  <li>Metabolic flexibility — crucial for metabolic health, insulin sensitivity, and longevity</li>
</ul>

<h3>What HIIT Develops (That Zone 2 Doesn't):</h3>
<ul>
  <li>VO2 max (maximal aerobic capacity)</li>
  <li>Anaerobic capacity and lactate tolerance</li>
  <li>Fast-twitch muscle fibre adaptations</li>
  <li>Power output at high intensities</li>
</ul>

<p>Both adaptations matter for long-term health and performance. VO2 max is one of the strongest predictors of all-cause mortality in the research literature. Zone 2 develops the mitochondrial infrastructure; HIIT expands the ceiling. You need both — you just need more Zone 2 than most people currently do.</p>

<h2>The Zone 2 Training Protocol</h2>

<p>Here's what the research and practitioner recommendations translate to for a non-professional athlete:</p>

<h3>Minimum Effective Dose</h3>
<p><strong>3 hours per week</strong> is the commonly cited minimum to see meaningful adaptation. Less than this produces some benefit but adaptation is slow. This is one of the reasons Zone 2 training is harder to fit into modern schedules than it sounds — you need genuine volume, not 20-minute sessions.</p>

<h3>Session Length</h3>
<p>Longer sessions are more valuable than shorter ones at this intensity. A 45-minute Zone 2 session is better than three 15-minute sessions of the same total time. The metabolic signalling from sustained steady-state work is different from intermittent bouts. Aim for sessions of <strong>45–90 minutes</strong>. Shorter than 30 minutes barely scratches the surface of Zone 2 adaptation.</p>

<h3>Frequency</h3>
<p>3–5 sessions per week is the target range. Elite endurance athletes do far more, but for health and longevity goals, 3–4 sessions averaging 45–60 minutes each gets you to the target weekly volume with manageable time commitment.</p>

<h3>Modalities</h3>
<p>Any sustained aerobic activity can be Zone 2. The best one is whichever you'll do consistently:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Cycling (indoor or outdoor)</strong> — San Millán's preferred modality, lowest injury risk, easy to control intensity</li>
  <li><strong>Brisk walking / hiking</strong> — genuinely effective for many people, especially those starting from a low fitness base where walking reaches Zone 2 intensity</li>
  <li><strong>Running</strong> — effective but injury risk is higher with volume, and slower runners may find true Zone 2 running feels uncomfortably slow</li>
  <li><strong>Rowing machine</strong> — excellent Zone 2 tool, full body engagement</li>
  <li><strong>Swimming</strong> — good option, but heart rate interpretation is different in water (aquatic HR is typically 10–15 bpm lower at equivalent exertion)</li>
</ul>

<h3>The Slowness Problem</h3>
<p>One of the most common Zone 2 mistakes: going too fast. Most recreational athletes, when told to do "easy cardio," still go harder than true Zone 2. The honest reality for many runners: true Zone 2 running feels embarrassingly slow. You may be passed by joggers. This is fine and correct. Your ego is not the training target — your mitochondria are.</p>

<p>Use heart rate monitoring to stay honest. If you drift above your Zone 2 ceiling consistently, slow down. Walk if needed. The adaptation happens at this specific intensity, not above it.</p>

<h2>Building Your Zone 2 Base: A 12-Week Ramp</h2>

<p>If you're coming from little cardio background, ramping volume too fast leads to overuse injury and burnout. Here's a sensible progression:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Weeks 1–4:</strong> 3 sessions/week, 30–40 minutes each (~1.5–2 hours/week). Establish the habit and get heart rate monitoring calibrated.</li>
  <li><strong>Weeks 5–8:</strong> 3–4 sessions/week, 40–50 minutes each (~2.5–3 hours/week). Hitting the minimum effective dose.</li>
  <li><strong>Weeks 9–12:</strong> 4 sessions/week, 45–60 minutes each (~3–4 hours/week). Full protocol maintenance.</li>
</ul>

<p>After 12 weeks of consistent Zone 2 training, most people notice significant improvement in their resting heart rate, perceived effort at the same pace, and ability to hold conversations at intensities that previously felt hard.</p>

<h2>Zone 2 and Longevity: Why Attia and San Millán Emphasise It</h2>

<p>The longevity case for Zone 2 comes from multiple directions:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Metabolic health:</strong> Zone 2 training dramatically improves insulin sensitivity, glucose disposal, and mitochondrial function — all of which decline with age and are central to metabolic disease risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Cardiovascular efficiency:</strong> Stroke volume improvements from Zone 2 training mean your heart does more work with less effort — lower resting heart rate, better cardiac reserve.</li>
  <li><strong>Mitochondrial health:</strong> Mitochondrial decline is increasingly understood as a central driver of aging. Zone 2 is one of the most potent known stimuli for mitochondrial biogenesis (making new mitochondria) and improving existing mitochondrial function.</li>
  <li><strong>VO2 max relationship:</strong> A higher aerobic base from Zone 2 work allows you to raise your VO2 max ceiling with high-intensity training, and VO2 max is among the strongest single predictors of longevity in epidemiological data.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Combining Zone 2 with Strength Training</h2>

<p>Zone 2 and resistance training are complementary, not competing. The standard concern — "won't cardio kill my gains?" — applies to high-intensity concurrent training done incorrectly, not Zone 2 work. True Zone 2 intensity doesn't generate enough cortisol or metabolic disruption to interfere with muscle protein synthesis when scheduled appropriately.</p>

<p>Practical scheduling:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Zone 2 and strength training can be done on the same day — Zone 2 before strength is generally better (pre-fatiguing lower body with running before squats isn't ideal, but cycling then lifting works fine)</li>
  <li>Or alternate days: strength 3x/week, Zone 2 3–4x/week on remaining days</li>
  <li>The combination of Zone 2 and progressive resistance training is arguably the most evidence-backed protocol for men optimising both longevity and body composition simultaneously</li>
</ul>

<p>For the resistance training side of the equation, see our <a href="/blog/workouts-training/optimal-morning-routine-body-composition">optimal morning routine guide</a>, which covers exercise sequencing and timing for body composition. And for the nutrition that supports both aerobic and strength adaptation, our <a href="/blog/diet-nutrition/how-much-protein-do-you-need">protein intake guide</a> covers the fuelling side.</p>

<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Zone 2 cardio benefits are real and well-supported by research — particularly San Millán's work on mitochondrial adaptations and metabolic health. But the vague "easy cardio, conversational pace" advice that most content regurgitates doesn't give you enough to train productively.</p>

<p>The protocol in numbers: 60–75% of max HR, conversation-effortful pace, 45–90 minute sessions, 3–4x per week, 3+ hours total weekly volume. That's the minimum effective dose for meaningful adaptation.</p>

<p>It takes weeks to feel, and months to measure. But the men who've built a serious Zone 2 base consistently report that it changes everything — their energy, their recovery from harder efforts, their resting metabolic health markers. It's one of the highest-ROI investments in the longevity toolkit once you get past the initial awkwardness of going slow enough to stay in zone.</p>

